<dl id="n08088d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08088d">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08088d"> 88(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ &mdash; treason</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Another natural consequence of the power of the Norman upper classes is that most of the terms pertaining to the law are of French origin &hellip;. <i>Petty</i> (Fr. petit) was, I suspect, introduced by the jurists in such combinations as &hellip; <i>petty constable</i>, &hellip; <i>petty treason</i> &hellip;, etc., before it was used commonly. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 85-6</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
